profitable communication, than mer

owne naughtie deedes. Bee the glad
der for it, if thou displeasest evil men,
and impute the evill opinions, which
naughtie men have of thee: for the
best praise that can be given thee. The
hardest worke of continencie, is, to
put away the soothing couresies of
dissembling flatterers, whose faw
ning wordes undoe the minde with
pleasant sensualitie. Presume not too
much upon thy selfe, neither bee thou
arrogant. Submit thy selfe so farre as
thou maiest keepe thy gravitie, and
yet make not thy selfe a footestoole
or cushen for everie man to leane on.
Be tolde of thy faultes willingly, and
suffer thy selfe gladly to be reprehen
ded, If anie man for a cause be angrie
with, and childe thee, acknowledge
thy fault, and let his chiding profite
thee. But if he chide thee without a
nie cause, thinke that thereby he would
have profited thee. Feare not sharpe
but sugred wordes. Doe thou thy selfe
eschue all fortes of vices, and bee not
an over busie searcher out of other
mens faultes, bee thou no sharpefault
finder, but an admonisher without
upbraiding, so that still thy warning
may beare the shewe of chearefull
mirth: and condiscent easily to par
don the errour. Neither praise nor
dispraise anie man overmuch. Be still
and give eare to them that speake, and
be readie to instruct them that doe
hearken: to him taht asketh give a
readie aunsweare, to him that despi
seth thee give place easily, and fall not
out to chiding and cursing. If thou
art continent, have an eye to the mo
tions of thy bodie and minde that they
be not unseemely: and set not light by
them, because no bodie seeth them:
For it maketh no matter if no bodie
see them, so thou thy selfe doest spie
and perceive them. Be mooveable not
